{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658334","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658334"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:46:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:46:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20729"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20729","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20729"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.15,0.63,0.13,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13605"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96786"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13605","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13605"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20729"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79401"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11578"},{"type":"tags","id":"11759"},{"type":"tags","id":"12606"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32713"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32714"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96786","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96786"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECells use modular signalling nodes to organise and coordinate complex cellular responses. These nodes contain multiple interacting proteins that must be precisely arranged in space and time.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of scaffold proteins in modular signalling nodes?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Directly catalyse enzymatic reactions to modify downstream signalling proteins","Generate second messenger molecules through activation of membrane-bound enzymes","Provide a physical framework for assembling signalling components","Degrade signalling proteins after activation through ubiquitin-mediated pathways","Directly bind to DNA response elements to regulate gene transcription"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProvide a physical framework for assembling signalling components\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct description of scaffold proteins in modular signalling nodes. Scaffold proteins contain multiple protein-binding domains that allow them to simultaneously bind several signalling components, organising them into functional complexes at specific subcellular locations. This spatial organisation increases signalling efficiency and specificity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirectly catalyse enzymatic reactions to modify downstream signalling proteins\u003C/strong\u003E - Most scaffold proteins lack intrinsic enzymatic activity; they primarily function to organise proteins with enzymatic activity rather than performing catalysis themselves\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenerate second messenger molecules through activation of membrane-bound enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E - Second messenger generation is typically performed by enzymes like adenylyl cyclase or phospholipase C, not by scaffold proteins\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDegrade signalling proteins after activation through ubiquitin-mediated pathways\u003C/strong\u003E - Scaffold proteins organise signalling complexes rather than participating in protein degradation, which is primarily performed by the ubiquitin-proteasome system\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirectly bind to DNA response elements to regulate gene transcription\u003C/strong\u003E - Scaffold proteins typically function in the cytoplasm or at membranes to organise signalling modules, not as transcription factors that bind DNA\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe modular organisation provided by scaffold proteins allows cells to achieve signalling specificity despite using many of the same proteins in different pathways. By compartmentalising signalling components, scaffold proteins can direct signals to specific downstream targets and facilitate cross-talk between different signalling pathways when needed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Modular signalling nodes are organised protein complexes that integrate multiple inputs and coordinate diverse cellular responses.","Scaffold proteins provide a physical framework for assembling signalling components into functional modules at specific subcellular locations.","Modular organisation of signalling proteins increases specificity and efficiency of signal transduction while enabling cross-talk between pathways."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 1, The Cell as a Unit of Health and Disease;  p. 19"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79401"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20729"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79401"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T21:58:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T21:59:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13605"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96786"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading"